Yes, that would work cleanly. The hook would drop `virtualItems` from its parameter list and instead expose a `load(page)` function. The two components would each supply their own trigger logic:

**`useThumbnailLoader` after the change:**
```ts
// No virtualItems param — just pdfPath and widthPx
// Returns { getSrc, isLoading, isFailed, invalidate, load }
```

**`ThumbnailPanel` — same logic as today, moved in:**
```ts
const { getSrc, isLoading, load, invalidate } = useThumbnailLoader(pdfPath, thumbWidth)

useEffect(() => {
  for (const item of virtualItems) load(item.index + 1)
})
```

**`DetailPanel` — simple single-page trigger:**
```ts
const { getSrc, isLoading, load, invalidate } = useThumbnailLoader(pdfPath, DETAIL_WIDTH)

useEffect(() => { load(pageNum) }, [pageNum, pdfPath])
```

The hook becomes a pure cache+RPC layer; the "when to load" policy stays in the component where it belongs. The only other change is renaming the hook to something that doesn't imply thumbnails specifically — `usePageLoader` would fit.

